## Option 2 — JFrog Generic Remote Repo for Composer

### Step 1: Create a Generic Remote Repository in JFrog

Ask your **JFrog Admin** to do the following:

**Artifactory UI → Repositories → Add Repositories → Remote Repository**

| Field | Value |
|---|---|
| **Package Type** | Generic |
| **Repository Key** | `devsecops-composer-remote` |
| **URL** | `https://getcomposer.org` |
| **Description** | Remote proxy for Composer binary |
| **Bypass HEAD Requests** | ✅ Enable |
| **Store Artifacts Locally** | ✅ Enable (caches after first download) |
| **Block Mismatching MIME Types** | ❌ Disable |

---

### Step 2: Add the Remote Repo to Your Virtual Repo

**Artifactory UI → Repositories → `itepaypg-sbiepay2-php-virtual` → Edit**

Under **Repositories** (included repos), add:
```
devsecops-composer-remote
```

So the final virtual repo includes:
```
devsecops-package-php-remote
devsecops-php-remote
devsecops-repo-php-remote
devsecops-composer-remote        ← ADD THIS
```

---

### Step 3: Verify the Path Resolves

Once done, test from any machine:

```bash
curl -k -u "JF_USER:JF_TOKEN" \
  "https://artifactory.jfrog.sbi/artifactory/itepaypg-sbiepay2-php-virtual/download/composer.phar" \
  -o /tmp/composer.phar

ls -lh /tmp/composer.phar   # Should be ~2.5MB+
```

> **Note the path:** Composer's download endpoint is `https://getcomposer.org/download/composer.phar` — so the artifact path through the remote proxy will be `/download/composer.phar`, **not** `/tools/composer/composer.phar`.

